ing chapters focus on specific research programs and theories, examining identity, affect, comparison processes, power and dependence, social exchange, status construction, and legitimacy. A concluding chapter provides an analysis of and commentary on the state of the theoretical programs in sociological social psychology. Contributors: Peter J. Burke, Joseph Berger, Coye Cheshire, Karen S. Cook, Pamela Emanuelson, Alexandra Gerbasi, Karen A. Hegtvedt, Michael A. Hogg, Guillermina Jasso, Edward J. Lawler, Michael W. Macy, George J. McCall, Linda D. Molm, Cecilia L. Ridgeway, Dawn T. Robinson, Lynn Smith-Lovin, Jan E. Stets, Jonathan H. Turner, Murray Webster Jr., David Willer, and Morris Zelditch, Jr.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aSocial psychologyxPhilosophy. 0aSocial psychology. 4aSociology -- Theory and Methods. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Research.2bisacsh1 aBerger, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurke, Peter J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurke, Peter J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCheshire, Coye, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Karen S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmanuelson, Pamela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerbasi, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHegtvedt, Karen A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHogg, Michael A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJasso, Guillermina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLawler, Edward J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacy, Michael W., econtributor.